013/**
014 * Contains code for manipulating colors as {@code int} and packed {@code float} values in the Oklab color space.
015 * Oklab is a very new color space that builds on the same foundation as IPT, but seems to be better-calibrated for
016 * uniform lightness and colorfulness, instead of just the emphasis on uniform hue that IPT has. Relative to IPT, Oklab
017 * has a noticeably smaller range in chromatic channels (IPT's protan and tritan can range past 0.8 or as low as 0.35,
018 * but the similar A and B channels in Oklab don't stray past about 0.65 at the upper end, if that), but it does this so
019 * the difference between two Oklab colors is just the Euclidean distance between their components. A slight difference
020 * between Oklab and IPT here is that IPT shrinks the chromatic channels to store their -1 to 1 range in a color float's
021 * 0 to 1 range, then offsets the shrunken range from -0.5 to 0.5, to 0 to 1; Oklab does not need to shrink the range,
022 * and only offsets it in the same way (both just add 0.5).
023 * <br>
024 * Here's <a href="https://bottosson.github.io/posts/oklab/">Bj√∂rn Ottosson's original post introducing Oklab</a>.
025 * So far, <a href="https://raphlinus.github.io/color/2021/01/18/oklab-critique.html">it stood up to analysis by Raph
026 * Levien</a>, and seems to be gaining fans quickly.
027 */
028public class ColorTools {
029        /**
030         * Gets a packed float representation of a color given as 4 float components, here, L (luminance or lightness), A
031         * (a chromatic component ranging from greenish to reddish, called protan in IPT), B (a chromatic component ranging
032         * from bluish to yellowish, called tritan in IPT), and alpha (or opacity). As long as you use a batch with
033         * {@link Shaders#fragmentShaderOklab} as its shader, colors passed with
034         * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setPackedColor(float)} will be interpreted as Oklab. L should be
035         * between 0 and 1, inclusive, with 0 used for very dark colors (almost only black), and 1 used for very light
036         * colors (almost only white). A and B range from 0.0 to 1.0, with grayscale results when both are about 0.5.
037         * There's some aesthetic value in changing just one chroma value. When A is high and B is low, the color is more
038         * purple/magenta, when both are low it is more bluish, when B is high and A is low, the color tends to be greenish,
039         * and when both are high it tends to be orange. When A and B are both near 0.5f, the color is closer to gray.
040         * Alpha is the multiplicative opacity of the color, and acts like RGBA's alpha.
041         * <br>
042         * This method bit-masks the resulting color's byte values, so any values can technically be given to this as
043         * L, A, and B, but they will only be reversible from the returned float color to the original L,
044         * A, and B values if the original values were in the range that {@link #channelL(float)}, {@link #channelA(float)},
045         * and {@link #channelB(float)} return. You can use {@link #inGamut(float, float, float)} to check if a given set of
046         * L, A, and B values is in-gamut, that is, it can be converted to and from an RGB color without going out of the
047         * valid range. If you just want to enforce that a color is in-gamut, you can use
048         * {@link #limitToGamut(float, float, float, float)}, which takes the same parameters this method does, or
049         * {@link #limitToGamut(float)} if you already have a packed float color that could be out-of-gamut.
050         *
051         * @param l     0f to 1f, lightness or L component of Oklab, with 0.5f meaning "no change" and 1f brightening
052         * @param a     0f to 1f, protan or A component of Oklab, with 1f more orange, red, or magenta
053         * @param b     0f to 1f, tritan or B component of Oklab, with 1f more green, yellow, or red
054         * @param alpha 0f to 1f, 0f makes the color transparent and 1f makes it opaque
055         * @return a float encoding a color with the given properties
056         */
057        public static float oklab(float l, float a, float b, float alpha) {
058                return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(((int) (alpha * 255) << 24 & 0xFE000000) | ((int) (b * 255) << 16 & 0xFF0000)
059                                | ((int) (a * 255) << 8 & 0xFF00) | ((int) (l * 255) & 0xFF));
060        }

063        /**
064         * An approximation of the cube-root function for float inputs and outputs.
065         * This can be about twice as fast as {@link Math#cbrt(double)}. This
066         * version does not tolerate negative inputs, because in the narrow use
067         * case it has in this class, it never is given negative inputs.
068         * <br>
069         * Has very low relative error (less than 1E-9) when inputs are uniformly
070         * distributed between 0 and 512, and absolute mean error of less than
071         * 1E-6 in the same scenario. Uses a bit-twiddling method similar to one
072         * presented in Hacker's Delight and also used in early 3D graphics (see
073         * https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_inverse_square_root for more, but
074         * this code approximates cbrt(x) and not 1/sqrt(x)). This specific code
075         * was originally by Marc B. Reynolds, posted in his "Stand-alone-junk"
076         * repo: https://github.com/Marc-B-Reynolds/Stand-alone-junk/blob/master/src/Posts/ballcube.c#L182-L197 .
077         * It's worth noting that while hardware instructions for finding the
078         * square root of a float have gotten extremely fast, the same is not
079         * true for the cube root (which has to allow negative inputs), so while
080         * the bit-twiddling inverse square root is no longer a beneficial
081         * optimization on current hardware, this does seem to help.
082         * <br>
083         * This is used when converting from RGB to Oklab, as an intermediate step.
084         * @param x any non-negative finite float to find the cube root of
085         * @return the cube root of x, approximated
086         */
087        private static float cbrtPositive(float x) {
088                int ix = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(x);
089                final float x0 = x;
090                ix = (ix>>>2) + (ix>>>4);
091                ix += (ix>>>4);
092                ix += (ix>>>8) + 0x2A5137A0;
093                x  = NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(ix);
094                x  = 0.33333334f*(2f * x + x0/(x*x));
095                x  = 0.33333334f*(2f * x + x0/(x*x));
096                return x;
097        }

099        /**
100         * Used when converting from Oklab to RGB, as an intermediate step.
101         * Really just {@code x * x * x}.
102         * @param x one of the LMS Prime channels to be converted to LMS
103         * @return an LMS channel value, which can be converted to RGB
104         */
105        private static float cube(final float x) {
106                return x * x * x;
107        }

109        /**
110         * Used when given non-linear sRGB inputs to make them linear, approximating with gamma 2.0.
111         * Really just {@code component * component}.
112         * @param component any non-linear channel of a color, to be made linear
113         * @return a linear version of component
114         */
115        private static float forwardGamma(final float component) {
116                return component * component;
117        }
118
119        /**
120         * Used to return from a linear, gamma-corrected input to an sRGB, non-linear output, using gamma 2.0.
121         * Really just a float version of the square root of component.
122         * @param component a linear channel of a color, to be made non-linear
123         * @return a non-linear version of component
124         */
125        private static float reverseGamma(final float component) {
126                return (float)Math.sqrt(component);
127        }

129        /**
130         * Converts a packed float color in the format produced by {@link ColorTools#oklab(float, float, float, float)} to an RGBA8888 int.
131         * This format of int can be used with Pixmap and in some other places in libGDX.
132         * @param packed a packed float color, as produced by {@link ColorTools#oklab(float, float, float, float)}
133         * @return an RGBA8888 int color
134         */
135        public static int toRGBA8888(final float packed)
136        {
137                final int decoded = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(packed);
138                final float L = (decoded & 0xff) / 255f;
139                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
140                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
141                final float l = cube(L + 0.3963377774f * A + 0.2158037573f * B);
142                final float m = cube(L - 0.1055613458f * A - 0.0638541728f * B);
143                final float s = cube(L - 0.0894841775f * A - 1.2914855480f * B);
144                final int r = (int)(reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(+4.0767245293f * l - 3.3072168827f * m + 0.2307590544f * s, 0f), 1f)) * 255.999f);
145                final int g = (int)(reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-1.2681437731f * l + 2.6093323231f * m - 0.3411344290f * s, 0f), 1f)) * 255.999f);
146                final int b = (int)(reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-0.0041119885f * l - 0.7034763098f * m + 1.7068625689f * s, 0f), 1f)) * 255.999f);
147                return r << 24 | g << 16 | b << 8 | (decoded & 0xfe000000) >>> 24 | decoded >>> 31;
148        }

151         * Converts a packed float color in the format produced by {@link ColorTools#oklab(float, float, float, float)}
152         * to a packed float in RGBA format.
153         * This format of float can be used with the standard SpriteBatch and in some other places in libGDX.
154         * @param packed a packed float color, as produced by {@link ColorTools#oklab(float, float, float, float)}
155         * @return a packed float color as RGBA
156         */
157        public static float toRGBA(final float packed)
158        {
159                final int decoded = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(packed);
160                final float L = (decoded & 0xff) / 255f;
161                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
162                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
163                final float l = cube(L + 0.3963377774f * A + 0.2158037573f * B);
164                final float m = cube(L - 0.1055613458f * A - 0.0638541728f * B);
165                final float s = cube(L - 0.0894841775f * A - 1.2914855480f * B);
166                final int r = (int)(reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(+4.0767245293f * l - 3.3072168827f * m + 0.2307590544f * s, 0f), 1f)) * 255.999f);
167                final int g = (int)(reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-1.2681437731f * l + 2.6093323231f * m - 0.3411344290f * s, 0f), 1f)) * 255.999f);
168                final int b = (int)(reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-0.0041119885f * l - 0.7034763098f * m + 1.7068625689f * s, 0f), 1f)) * 255.999f);
169                return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(r | g << 8 | b << 16 | (decoded & 0xfe000000));
170        }

172        /**
173         * Writes an Oklab-format packed float color (the format produced by {@link ColorTools#oklab(float, float, float, float)})
174         * into an RGBA8888 Color as used by libGDX (called {@code editing}).
175         * @param editing a libGDX color that will be filled in-place with an RGBA conversion of {@code packed}
176         * @param packed a packed float color, as produced by {@link ColorTools#oklab(float, float, float, float)}
177         * @return an RGBA8888 int color
178         */
179        public static Color toColor(Color editing, final float packed)
180        {
181                final int decoded = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(packed);
182                final float L = (decoded & 0xff) / 255f;
183                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
184                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
185                final float l = cube(L + 0.3963377774f * A + 0.2158037573f * B);
186                final float m = cube(L - 0.1055613458f * A - 0.0638541728f * B);
187                final float s = cube(L - 0.0894841775f * A - 1.2914855480f * B);
188                editing.r = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(+4.0767245293f * l - 3.3072168827f * m + 0.2307590544f * s, 0f), 1f));
189                editing.g = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-1.2681437731f * l + 2.6093323231f * m - 0.3411344290f * s, 0f), 1f));
190                editing.b = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-0.0041119885f * l - 0.7034763098f * m + 1.7068625689f * s, 0f), 1f));
191                editing.a = (decoded >>> 25) * 0x1.020408p-7f; // this is 1/127 as a float
192                return editing.clamp();
193        }

196         * Writes an Oklab-format packed float color (the format produced by {@link ColorTools#oklab(float, float, float, float)})
197         * into an Oklab-format Color called {@code editing}. This is mostly useful if the rest of your application expects
198         * colors in Oklab format, such as because you use {@link Shaders#fragmentShaderOklab} or {@link ColorfulBatch}.
199         * <br>
200         * Internally, this simply calls {@link Color#abgr8888ToColor(Color, float)} and returns the edited Color.
201         * @param editing a libGDX Color that will be filled in-place with the color {@code oklab}, unchanged from its color space
202         * @param oklab a packed float color, as produced by {@link ColorTools#oklab(float, float, float, float)}
203         * @return an RGBA8888 int color
204         */
205        public static Color toOklabColor(Color editing, final float oklab){
206                Color.abgr8888ToColor(editing, oklab);
207                return editing;
208        }

210        /**
211         * Takes a color encoded as an RGBA8888 int and converts to a packed float in the Oklab format this uses.
212         * @param rgba an int with the channels (in order) red, green, blue, alpha; should have 8 bits per channel
213         * @return a packed float as Oklab, which this class can use
214         */
215        public static float fromRGBA8888(final int rgba) {
216                final float r = forwardGamma((rgba >>> 24) * 0x1.010101010101p-8f);
217                final float g = forwardGamma((rgba >>> 16 & 0xFF) * 0x1.010101010101p-8f);
218                final float b = forwardGamma((rgba >>> 8 & 0xFF) * 0x1.010101010101p-8f);
219
220                final float l = cbrtPositive(0.4121656120f * r + 0.5362752080f * g + 0.0514575653f * b);
221                final float m = cbrtPositive(0.2118591070f * r + 0.6807189584f * g + 0.1074065790f * b);
222                final float s = cbrtPositive(0.0883097947f * r + 0.2818474174f * g + 0.6302613616f * b);
223
224                return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(
225                                      Math.min(Math.max((int)((0.2104542553f * l + 0.7936177850f * m - 0.0040720468f * s) * 255.999f         ), 0), 255)
226                                                | Math.min(Math.max((int)((1.9779984951f * l - 2.4285922050f * m + 0.4505937099f * s) * 127.999f + 127.5f), 0), 255) << 8
227                                                | Math.min(Math.max((int)((0.0259040371f * l + 0.7827717662f * m - 0.8086757660f * s) * 127.999f + 127.5f), 0), 255) << 16
228                                                | (rgba & 0xFE) << 24);
229        }

232         * Takes a color encoded as an RGBA8888 packed float and converts to a packed float in the Oklab format this uses.
233         * @param packed a packed float in RGBA8888 format, with A in the MSB and R in the LSB
234         * @return a packed float as Oklab, which this class can use
235         */
236        public static float fromRGBA(final float packed) {
237                final int abgr = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(packed);
238                final float r = forwardGamma((abgr & 0xFF) * 0x1.010101010101p-8f);
239                final float g = forwardGamma((abgr >>> 8 & 0xFF) * 0x1.010101010101p-8f);
240                final float b = forwardGamma((abgr >>> 16 & 0xFF) * 0x1.010101010101p-8f);
241                final float l = cbrtPositive(0.4121656120f * r + 0.5362752080f * g + 0.0514575653f * b);
242                final float m = cbrtPositive(0.2118591070f * r + 0.6807189584f * g + 0.1074065790f * b);
243                final float s = cbrtPositive(0.0883097947f * r + 0.2818474174f * g + 0.6302613616f * b);
244                return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(
245                                          Math.min(Math.max((int)((0.2104542553f * l + 0.7936177850f * m - 0.0040720468f * s) * 255.999f         ), 0), 255)
246                                                | Math.min(Math.max((int)((1.9779984951f * l - 2.4285922050f * m + 0.4505937099f * s) * 127.999f + 127.5f), 0), 255) << 8
247                                                | Math.min(Math.max((int)((0.0259040371f * l + 0.7827717662f * m - 0.8086757660f * s) * 127.999f + 127.5f), 0), 255) << 16

261        /**
262         * Takes a libGDX Color that uses RGBA8888 channels and converts to a packed float in the Oklab format this uses.
263         * @param color a libGDX RGBA8888 Color
264         * @return a packed float as Oklab, which this class can use
265         */
266        public static float fromColor(final Color color) {
267                final float r = forwardGamma(color.r);
268                final float g = forwardGamma(color.g);
269                final float b = forwardGamma(color.b);
270                final float l = cbrtPositive(0.4121656120f * r + 0.5362752080f * g + 0.0514575653f * b);
271                final float m = cbrtPositive(0.2118591070f * r + 0.6807189584f * g + 0.1074065790f * b);
272                final float s = cbrtPositive(0.0883097947f * r + 0.2818474174f * g + 0.6302613616f * b);
273                return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(
274                                          Math.min(Math.max((int)((0.2104542553f * l + 0.7936177850f * m - 0.0040720468f * s) * 255.999f         ), 0), 255)
275                                                | Math.min(Math.max((int)((1.9779984951f * l - 2.4285922050f * m + 0.4505937099f * s) * 127.999f + 127.5f), 0), 255) << 8
276                                                | Math.min(Math.max((int)((0.0259040371f * l + 0.7827717662f * m - 0.8086757660f * s) * 127.999f + 127.5f), 0), 255) << 16
277                                                | ((int)(color.a * 255f) << 24 & 0xFE000000));
278        }

294                final float s = cbrtPositive(0.0883097947f * r + 0.2818474174f * g + 0.6302613616f * b);

296                                          Math.min(Math.max((int)((0.2104542553f * l + 0.7936177850f * m - 0.0040720468f * s) * 255.999f         ), 0), 255)

353        /**
354         * Gets the alpha channel value of the given encoded color, as an even int ranging from 0 to 254, inclusive. Because

425        /**
426         * Gets the "chroma" or "colorfulness" of a given Oklab color. Chroma is similar to saturation in that grayscale
427         * values have 0 saturation and 0 chroma, while brighter colors have high saturation and chroma. The difference is
428         * that colors that are perceptually more-colorful have higher chroma than colors that are perceptually
429         * less-colorful, regardless of hue, whereas saturation changes its meaning depending on the hue and lightness. That
430         * is, the most saturated color for a given hue and lightness always has a saturation of 1, but if that color
431         * isn't perceptually very colorful (as is the case for very dark and very light colors), it will have a chroma that
432         * is much lower than the maximum. The result of this method can't be negative, grayscale values have very close to
433         * 0 chroma, and the most colorful values (all very close to magenta) should have 0.31613f chroma.
434         * @param encoded a color as a packed float that can be obtained by {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)}
435         * @return a float between 0.0f and 0.31613f that represents how colorful the given value is
436         */
437        public static float chroma(final float encoded) {
438                final int decoded = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(encoded);
439                final float a = ((decoded >>> 7 & 0x1FE) - 255) / 510f;
440                final float b = ((decoded >>> 15 & 0x1FE) - 255) / 510f;
441                return (float) Math.sqrt(a * a + b * b);
442        }

444        /**
445         * Given a hue and lightness, this gets the (approximate) maximum chroma possible for that hue-lightness
446         * combination. This is useful to know the bounds of {@link #chroma(float)}. This should be no greater
447         * than 0.31613f .
448         * @param hue the hue, typically between 0.0f and 1.0f, to look up
449         * @param lightness the lightness, clamped between 0.0f and 1.0f, to look up
450         * @return the maximum possible chroma for the given hue and lightness, between 0.0f and 0.31613f
451         */
452        public static float chromaLimit(final float hue, final float lightness){
453                final int idx = (int) (Math.min(Math.max(lightness, 0f), 1f) * 255.999f) << 8
454                                | (int) (256f * (hue - MathUtils.floor(hue)));
455                return GAMUT_DATA[idx] * 0x1p-8f;
456        }

458        /**
459         * Gets a color as an Oklab packed float given floats representing hue, saturation, lightness, and opacity.
460         * All parameters should normally be between 0 and 1 inclusive, though any hue is tolerated (precision loss may
461         * affect the color if the hue is too large). A hue of 0 is red, progressively higher hue values go to orange,
462         * yellow, green, blue, and purple before wrapping around to red as it approaches 1. A saturation of 0 is grayscale,
463         * a saturation of 1 is brightly colored, and values close to 1 will usually appear more distinct than values close
464         * to 0, especially if the hue is different. A lightness of 0.001f or less is always black (also using a shortcut if
465         * this is the case, respecting opacity), while a lightness of 1f is white. Very bright colors are mostly in a band
466         * of high-saturation where lightness is 0.5f.
467         * <br>
468         * This method considers its hue, saturation, and lightness parameters as the HSL color space does. You may instead
469         * want the method {@link #oklabByHSL(float, float, float, float)}, which treats lightness exactly as Oklab does,
470         * and handles hue and saturation with the Oklab color solid (which is shaped oddly) instead of the HSL color solid
471         * (which is a bicone, with a wide cone pointing up attached at the base to another wide cone pointing down).
472         * Using oklabByHSL() should be faster in many cases, and the lightness handling alone may be a reason to use it.
473         * There is also {@link #oklabByHCL(float, float, float, float)}, which may be preferable if you want a specific
474         * amount of chroma (colorful-ness) and no greater.
475         *
476         * @param hue        0f to 1f, color wheel position
477         * @param saturation 0f to 1f, 0f is grayscale and 1f is brightly colored
478         * @param lightness  0f to 1f, 0f is black and 1f is white
479         * @param opacity    0f to 1f, 0f is fully transparent and 1f is opaque
480         * @return a float encoding a color with the given properties
481         */
482        public static float floatGetHSL(float hue, float saturation, float lightness, float opacity) {
483                if (lightness <= 0.001f) {
484                        return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat((((int) (opacity * 255f) << 24) & 0xFE000000) | 0x7F7F00);
485                } else {
486                        return fromRGBA(FloatColors.hsl2rgb(hue, saturation, lightness, opacity));
487                }
488        }

490        /**
491         * Gets the saturation of the given encoded color as HSL would calculate it, as a float ranging from 0.0f to 1.0f,
492         * inclusive. This is different from {@link #chroma(float)}; see that method's documentation for details. It is also
493         * different from {@link #oklabSaturation(float)}, which gets the saturation as Oklab understands it rather than how
494         * HSL understands it.
495         *
496         * @param encoded a color as a packed float that can be obtained by {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)}
497         * @return the saturation of the color from 0.0 (a grayscale color; inclusive) to 1.0 (a bright color, inclusive)
498         */
499        public static float saturation(final float encoded) {
500                final int decoded = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(encoded);
501                final float L = (decoded & 0xff) / 255f;
502                if(Math.abs(L - 0.5) > 0.495f) return 0f;
503                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
504                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
505                final float l = cube(L + 0.3963377774f * A + 0.2158037573f * B);
506                final float m = cube(L - 0.1055613458f * A - 0.0638541728f * B);
507                final float s = cube(L - 0.0894841775f * A - 1.2914855480f * B);
508                final float r = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(+4.0767245293f * l - 3.3072168827f * m + 0.2307590544f * s, 0f), 1f));
509                final float g = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-1.2681437731f * l + 2.6093323231f * m - 0.3411344290f * s, 0f), 1f));
510                final float b = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-0.0041119885f * l - 0.7034763098f * m + 1.7068625689f * s, 0f), 1f));
511                float x, y, w;
512                if(g < b) {
513                        x = b;
514                        y = g;
515                }
516                else {
517                        x = g;
518                        y = b;
519                }
520                if(r < x) {
521                        w = r;
522                }
523                else {
524                        w = x;
525                        x = r;
526                }
527                return x - Math.min(w, y);
528        }

531         * Defined as per HSL; normally you only need {@link #channelL(float)} to get accurate lightness for Oklab. You can
532         * also use {@link #oklabLightness(float)}, which is an alias for channelL(). This ranges from 0.0f (black) to 1.0f

543                final float l = cube(L + 0.3963377774f * A + 0.2158037573f * B);
544                final float m = cube(L - 0.1055613458f * A - 0.0638541728f * B);
545                final float s = cube(L - 0.0894841775f * A - 1.2914855480f * B);
546                final float r = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(+4.0767245293f * l - 3.3072168827f * m + 0.2307590544f * s, 0f), 1f));
547                final float g = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-1.2681437731f * l + 2.6093323231f * m - 0.3411344290f * s, 0f), 1f));
548                final float b = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-0.0041119885f * l - 0.7034763098f * m + 1.7068625689f * s, 0f), 1f));
549                float x, y, w;
550                if(g < b) {
551                        x = b;
552                        y = g;
553                }
554                else {
555                        x = g;

562                        w = x;

569        /**
570         * Gets the hue of the given encoded color, as a float from 0f (inclusive, red and approaching orange if increased)
571         * to 1f (exclusive, red and approaching purple if decreased). You can also use {@link #oklabHue(float)}, which
572         * positions the different hues at different values, somewhat, from this, but is more accurate to how Oklab handles
573         * hues.
574         *
575         * @param encoded a color as a packed float that can be obtained by {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)}
576         * @return The hue of the color from 0.0 (red, inclusive) towards orange, then yellow, and
577         * eventually to purple before looping back to almost the same red (1.0, exclusive)
578         */
579        public static float hue(final float encoded) {
580                final int decoded = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(encoded);
581                final float L = (decoded & 0xff) / 255f;
582                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
583                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
584                final float l = cube(L + 0.3963377774f * A + 0.2158037573f * B);
585                final float m = cube(L - 0.1055613458f * A - 0.0638541728f * B);
586                final float s = cube(L - 0.0894841775f * A - 1.2914855480f * B);
587                final float r = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(+4.0767245293f * l - 3.3072168827f * m + 0.2307590544f * s, 0f), 1f));
588                final float g = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-1.2681437731f * l + 2.6093323231f * m - 0.3411344290f * s, 0f), 1f));
589                final float b = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-0.0041119885f * l - 0.7034763098f * m + 1.7068625689f * s, 0f), 1f));
590                float x, y, z, w;
591                if(g < b) {
592                        x = b;
593                        y = g;
594                        z = -1f;
595                        w = 2f / 3f;
596                }
597                else {
598                        x = g;
599                        y = b;
600                        z = 0f;
601                        w = -1f / 3f;
602                }
603                if(r < x) {
604                        z = w;
605                        w = r;
606                }
607                else {
608                        w = x;
609                        x = r;
610                }
611                float d = x - Math.min(w, y);
612                return Math.abs(z + (w - y) / (6f * d + 1e-10f));
613        }

653        /**
654         * Gets a variation on the packed float color basis as another packed float that has its hue, saturation, lightness,
655         * and opacity adjusted by the specified amounts. Note that this edits the color in HSL space, not Oklab! Takes
656         * floats representing the amounts of change to apply to hue, saturation, lightness, and opacity; these can be
657         * between -1f and 1f. Returns a float that can be used as a packed or encoded color with methods like
658         * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setPackedColor(float)}. The float is likely to be different than the
659         * result of {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)} unless hue, saturation, lightness, and opacity are all 0.
660         * This won't allocate any objects.
661         * <br>
662         * The parameters this takes all specify additive changes for a color component, clamping the final values so they
663         * can't go above 1 or below 0, with an exception for hue, which can rotate around if lower or higher hues would be
664         * used. As an example, if you give this 0.4f for saturation, and the current color has saturation 0.7f, then the
665         * resulting color will have 1f for saturation. If you gave this -0.1f for saturation and the current color again
666         * has saturation 0.7f, then resulting color will have 0.6f for saturation.
667         * <br>
668         * You may want {@link #editOklab(float, float, float, float, float, float, float, float, float)} instead, which
669         * adjusts the L, A, B, and alpha channels directly instead of converting to HSL and back.
670         *
671         * @param basis      a packed float color that will be used as the starting point to make the next color
672         * @param hue        -1f to 1f, the hue change that can be applied to the new float color (not clamped, wraps)
673         * @param saturation -1f to 1f, the saturation change that can be applied to the new float color
674         * @param light      -1f to 1f, the light/brightness change that can be applied to the new float color
675         * @param opacity    -1f to 1f, the opacity/alpha change that can be applied to the new float color
676         * @return a float encoding a variation of basis with the given changes
677         */
678        public static float toEditedFloat(float basis, float hue, float saturation, float light, float opacity) {
679                final int decoded = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(basis);
680                final float L = Math.min(Math.max(light + (decoded & 0xff) / 255f, 0f), 1f);
681                opacity = Math.min(Math.max(opacity + (decoded >>> 24 & 0xfe) * 0x1.020408p-8f, 0f), 1f);
682                if (L <= 0.001f)
683                        return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat((((int) (opacity * 255f) << 24) & 0xFE000000) | 0x808000);
684                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
685                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
686                final float l = cube(L + 0.3963377774f * A + 0.2158037573f * B);
687                final float m = cube(L - 0.1055613458f * A - 0.0638541728f * B);
688                final float s = cube(L - 0.0894841775f * A - 1.2914855480f * B);
689                final float r = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(+4.0767245293f * l - 3.3072168827f * m + 0.2307590544f * s, 0f), 1f));
690                final float g = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-1.2681437731f * l + 2.6093323231f * m - 0.3411344290f * s, 0f), 1f));
691                final float b = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-0.0041119885f * l - 0.7034763098f * m + 1.7068625689f * s, 0f), 1f));
692                float x, y, z, w;
693                if(g < b) {
694                        x = b;
695                        y = g;
696                        z = -1f;
697                        w = 2f / 3f;
698                }
699                else {
700                        x = g;
701                        y = b;
702                        z = 0f;
703                        w = -1f / 3f;
704                }
705                if(r < x) {
706                        z = w;
707                        w = r;
708                }
709                else {
710                        w = x;
711                        x = r;
712                }
713                final float d = x - Math.min(w, y);
714                final float lum = x * (1f - 0.5f * d / (x + 1e-10f));
715                hue += Math.abs(z + (w - y) / (6f * d + 1e-10f)) + 1f;
716                saturation += (x - lum) / (Math.min(lum, 1f - lum) + 1e-10f);
717                return fromRGBA(FloatColors.hsl2rgb(hue - (int)hue, Math.min(Math.max(saturation, 0f), 1f), lum, opacity));
718        }

752        /**
753         * Interpolates from the packed float color start towards a warmer color (orange to magenta) by change. While change
754         * should be between 0f (return start as-is) and 1f (return fully warmed), start should be a packed color, as from
755         * {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)}. This is a good way to reduce allocations of temporary Colors,

889        /**
890         * Given a packed float Oklab color {@code mainColor} and another Oklab color that it should be made to contrast with,
891         * gets a packed float Oklab color with roughly inverted L but the same chromatic channels and opacity (A and B
892         * are likely to be clamped if the result gets close to white or black). This won't ever produce black or other very
893         * dark colors, and also has a gap in the range it produces for L values between 0.5 and 0.55. That allows
894         * most of the colors this method produces to contrast well as a foreground when displayed on a background of
895         * {@code contrastingColor}, or vice versa. This will leave the L unchanged if the chromatic channels of the
896         * contrastingColor and those of the mainColor are already very different. This has nothing to do with the contrast
897         * channel of the tweak in ColorfulBatch; where that part of the tweak can make too-similar lightness values further
898         * apart by just a little, this makes a modification on {@code mainColor} to maximize its lightness difference from
899         * {@code contrastingColor} without losing its other qualities.
900         * @param mainColor a packed float color, as produced by {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)};
901         *                     this is the color that will be adjusted
902         * @param contrastingColor a packed float color, as produced by {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)};
903         *                            the adjusted mainColor will contrast with this
904         * @return a different Oklab packed float color, based on mainColor but with potentially very different lightness
905         */
906        public static float inverseLightness(final float mainColor, final float contrastingColor)
907        {
908                final int bits = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(mainColor),
909                                contrastBits = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(contrastingColor),
910                                L = (bits & 0xff),
911                                A = (bits >>> 8 & 0xff),
912                                B = (bits >>> 16 & 0xff),
913                                cL = (contrastBits & 0xff),
914                                cA = (contrastBits >>> 8 & 0xff),
915                                cB = (contrastBits >>> 16 & 0xff);
916                if((A - cA) * (A - cA) + (B - cB) * (B - cB) >= 0x10000)
917                        return mainColor;
918                return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat((bits & 0xFEFFFF00) | (int) (cL < 128 ? L * 0.45f + 140 : 127 - L * 0.45f));
919        }

923         * with, gets a packed float Oklab color with L that should be quite different from {@code contrastingColor}'s L,
924         * but the same chromatic channels and opacity (A and B are likely to be clamped if the result gets close to white
925         * or black). This allows most of the colors this method produces to contrast well as a foreground when displayed on
926         * a background of {@code contrastingColor}, or vice versa.
927         * <br>
928         * This is similar to {@link #inverseLightness(float, float)}, but is considerably simpler, and this method will
929         * change the lightness of mainColor when the two given colors have close lightness but distant chroma. Because it
930         * averages the original L of mainColor with the modified one, this tends to not produce harsh color changes.

933         * @return a different packed Oklab float color, based on mainColor but typically with different lightness

935        public static float differentiateLightness(final float mainColor, final float contrastingColor)
936        {
937                final int main = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(mainColor), contrast = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(contrastingColor);
938                return limitToGamut(NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat((main & 0xFEFFFF00) | (contrast + 128 & 0xFF) + (main & 0xFF) >>> 1));
939        }

953        /**
954         * Makes the additive Oklab color stored in {@code color} cause less of a change when used as a tint, as if it were
955         * mixed with neutral gray. When {@code fraction} is 1.0, this returns color unchanged; when fraction is 0.0, it
956         * returns {@link Palette#GRAY}, and when it is in-between 0.0 and 1.0 it returns something between the two. This is
957         * meant for things like area of effect abilities that make smaller color changes toward their periphery.
958         * @param color a color that should have its tinting effect potentially weakened
959         * @param fraction how much of {@code color} should be kept, from 0.0 to 1.0
960         * @return an Oklab float color between gray and {@code color}
961         */
962        public static float lessenChange(final float color, float fraction) {
963                final int e = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(color),
964                                sL = 0x80, sA = 0x80, sB = 0x80, sAlpha = 0xFE,
965                                eL = (e & 0xFF), eA = (e >>> 8) & 0xFF, eB = (e >>> 16) & 0xFF, eAlpha = e >>> 24 & 0xFE;
966                return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(((int) (sL + fraction * (eL - sL)) & 0xFF)
967                                | (((int) (sA + fraction * (eA - sA)) & 0xFF) << 8)
968                                | (((int) (sB + fraction * (eB - sB)) & 0xFF) << 16)
969                                | (((int) (sAlpha + fraction * (eAlpha - sAlpha)) & 0xFE) << 24));

972        /**
973         * Makes a quasi-randomly-edited variant on the given {@code color}, allowing typically a small amount of
974         * {@code variance} (such as 0.05 to 0.25) between the given color and what this can return. The {@code seed} should
975         * be different each time this is called, and can be obtained from a random number generator to make the colors more
976         * random, or can be incremented on each call. If the seed is only incremented or decremented, then this shouldn't
977         * produce two similar colors in a row unless variance is very small. The variance affects the L, A, and B of the
978         * generated color, and each of those channels can go up or down by the given variance as long as the total distance
979         * isn't greater than the variance (this considers A and B extra-wide, going from -1 to 1, while L goes from 0 to 1,
980         * but only internally for measuring distance).
981         * @param color a packed float color, as produced by {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)}
982         * @param seed a long seed that should be different on each call; should not be 0
983         * @param variance max amount of difference between the given color and the generated color; always less than 1
984         * @return a generated packed float color that should be at least somewhat different from {@code color}
985         */
986        public static float randomEdit(final float color, long seed, final float variance) {
987                final int decoded = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(color);
988                final float L = (decoded & 0xff) / 255f;
989                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
990                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
991                final float limit = variance * variance;
992                float dist, x, y, z;
993                for (int j = 0; j < 50; j++) {
994                        x = (((seed * 0xD1B54A32D192ED03L >>> 41) - 0x7FFFFFp-1f) * 0x1p-22f) * variance;
995                        y = (((seed * 0xABC98388FB8FAC03L >>> 41) - 0x7FFFFFp-1f) * 0x1p-22f) * variance;
996                        z = (((seed * 0x8CB92BA72F3D8DD7L >>> 41) - 0x7FFFFFp-1f) * 0x1p-22f) * variance;
997                        seed += 0x9E3779B97F4A7C15L;
998                        dist = x * x + y * y + z * z;
999                        if(dist <= limit && inGamut(x += L, y = (A + y) * 0.5f + 0.5f, z = (B + z) * 0.5f + 0.5f))
1000                                return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat((decoded & 0xFE000000) | ((int)(z * 255.5f) << 16 & 0xFF0000)
1001                                        | ((int)(y * 255.5f) << 8 & 0xFF00) | (int)(x * 255.5f));
1002                }
1003                return color;
1004        }

1017        /**
1018         * Given a 1D int index between 0 and 65535 (both inclusive), this treats the 1D index as two parts (lightness and
1019         * hue angle, both from 0 to 255) and gets the distance from grayscale to the edge of the gamut at that lightness
1020         * and hue. The index can be constructed from a lightness value {@code L} from 0 to 255, and a hue value {@code H}
1021         * from 0 to 255 with: {@code (L << 8 | H)} or the simpler equivalent {@code (L * 256 + H)}. These assume L and H
1022         * have been limited to the 0 to 255 range already. This does not bounds-check index. Because hue is not typically
1023         * measured between 0 and 255, getting that value is a bit different; you can use
1024         * {@link TrigTools#atan2_(float, float)} (with an Oklab color's B for y, then its A for x) and multiply it by 256
1025         * to get H.
1026         * <br>
1027         * The distance this returns is a byte between 0 and 82 (both inclusive), as the Euclidean distance from the center
1028         * grayscale value at the lightness in the index, to the edge of the gamut at the same lightness, along the hue in
1029         * the index. This is measured in a space from -1 to 1 for both A and B, with the 0 in the center meaning grayscale,
1030         * and multiplied by 256 to get a meaningful byte value. To return to the A and B values Oklab uses here, you would
1031         * need to use some trigonometry on the hue (if it's in the 0 to 1 range, you can call
1032         * {@link TrigTools#cos_(float)} on the hue to almost get A, and {@link TrigTools#sin_(float)} to almost get B),
1033         * then multiply each of those by the distance, divide each by 256.0, and add 0.5.
1034         * <br>
1035         * Only intended for the narrow cases where external code needs read-only access to the internal Oklab gamut data.
1036         * The gamut data is quite large (the Oklab ColorTools file is 236 KB at the time of writing, while the IPT_HQ
1037         * ColorTools file is just 56 KB, with the main difference being the sizable exact gamut), so it's better to have
1038         * direct read access to it without being able to accidentally rewrite it.
1039         * @param index must be between 0 and 65535; the upper 8 bits are lightness and the lower 8 are hue angle.
1040         * @return a byte (always between 0 and 82, inclusive) representing the Euclidean distance between a grayscale value and the most saturated value possible, using the above measurements
1041         */
1042        public static byte getRawGamutValue(int index){
1043                return GAMUT_DATA[index];
1044        }

1046        /**
1047         * Returns true if the given packed float color, as Oklab, is valid to convert losslessly back to RGBA.
1048         * @param packed a packed float color as Oklab
1049         * @return true if the given packed float color can be converted back and forth to RGBA
1050         */
1051        public static boolean inGamut(final float packed)
1052        {
1053                final int decoded = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(packed);
1054                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 255f;
1055                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 255f;
1056                final byte g = GAMUT_DATA[(decoded & 0xff) << 8 | (int)(256f * TrigTools.atan2_(B, A))];
1057                return g * g * 0x1p-18 >= (A * A + B * B);
1058        }

1060        /**
1061         * Returns true if the given Oklab values are valid to convert losslessly back to RGBA.
1062         * @param L lightness channel, as a float from 0 to 1
1063         * @param A green-to-red chromatic channel, as a float from 0 to 1
1064         * @param B blue-to-yellow chromatic channel, as a float from 0 to 1
1065         * @return true if the given Oklab channels can be converted back and forth to RGBA
1066         */
1067        public static boolean inGamut(float L, float A, float B)
1068        {
1069                A = (A - 0.5f);
1070                B = (B - 0.5f);
1071                final byte g = GAMUT_DATA[((int)(L * 255.999f) << 8) | (int)(256f * TrigTools.atan2_(B, A))];
1072                return g * g * 0x1p-18 >= (A * A + B * B);
1073        }

1075        /**
1076         * Gets the color with the same L as the Oklab color stored in the given packed float, but the furthest A
1077         * B from gray possible for that lightness while keeping the same hue as the given color. This is very
1078         * similar to calling {@link #enrich(float, float)} with a very large {@code change} value.
1079         * @param packed a packed float color in Oklab format; does not need to be in-gamut
1080         * @return the color that is as far from grayscale as this can get while keeping the L and hue of packed
1081         * @see #limitToGamut(float) You can use limitToGamut() if you only want max saturation for out-of-gamut colors.
1082         */
1083        public static float maximizeSaturation(final float packed) {
1084                final int decoded = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(packed);
1085                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
1086                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
1087                final float hue = TrigTools.atan2_(B, A);
1088                final int idx = (decoded & 0xff) << 8 | (int) (256f * hue);
1089                final float dist = GAMUT_DATA[idx];
1090                return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(
1091                                (decoded & 0xFE0000FF) |
1092                                                (int) (TrigTools.cos_(hue) * dist + 128f) << 8 |
1093                                                (int) (TrigTools.sin_(hue) * dist + 128f) << 16);
1094        }
1095        /**
1096         * Gets the color with the same L as the Oklab color stored in the given packed float, but the furthest A
1097         * B from gray possible for that lightness while keeping the same hue as the given color. This is very
1098         * similar to calling {@link #enrich(float, float)} with a very large {@code change} value.
1099         * @param L lightness component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1100         * @param A green-to-red chromatic component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1101         * @param B blue-to-yellow chromatic component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1102         * @param alpha alpha component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1103         * @return the color that is as far from grayscale as this can get while keeping the L and hue of packed
1104         * @see #limitToGamut(float, float, float, float) You can use limitToGamut() if you only want max saturation
1105         * for out-of-gamut colors.
1106         */
1107        public static float maximizeSaturation(float L, float A, float B, float alpha) {
1108                L = Math.min(Math.max(L, 0f), 1f);
1109                A = Math.min(Math.max(A, 0f), 1f);
1110                B = Math.min(Math.max(B, 0f), 1f);
1111                alpha = Math.min(Math.max(alpha, 0f), 1f);
1112                final float A2 = (A - 0.5f);
1113                final float B2 = (B - 0.5f);
1114                final float hue = TrigTools.atan2_(B2, A2);
1115                final int idx = (int) (L * 255.999f) << 8 | (int) (256f * hue);
1116                final float dist = GAMUT_DATA[idx];
1117                return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(
1118                                (int) (alpha * 127.999f) << 25 |
1119                                                (int) (TrigTools.sin_(hue) * dist + 128f) << 16 |
1120                                                (int) (TrigTools.cos_(hue) * dist + 128f) << 8 |
1121                                                (int) (L * 255.999f));
1122        }

1140         * Gets the saturation of the given Oklab float color, but as Oklab understands saturation rather than how HSL does.
1141         * Saturation here is a fraction of the chroma limit (see {@link #chromaLimit(float, float)}) for a given hue and
1142         * lightness, and is between 0 and 1. This gives a float between 0 (inclusive) and 1 (inclusive).
1143         *
1144         * @param packed a packed Oklab float color
1145         * @return a float between 0 (inclusive) and 1 (inclusive) that represents saturation in the Oklab color space
1146         */
1147        public static float oklabSaturation(final float packed) {
1148                final int decoded = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(packed);
1149                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
1150                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
1151                final float hue = TrigTools.atan2_(B, A);
1152                final int idx = (decoded & 0xff) << 8 | (int) (256f * hue);
1153                final float dist = GAMUT_DATA[idx];

1170        /**
1171         * A different way to specify an Oklab color, using hue, saturation, lightness, and alpha like a normal HSL(A) color
1172         * but calculating them directly in the Oklab color space. This is more efficient than
1173         * {@link #floatGetHSL(float, float, float, float)}, but for colors with less than 0.5f lightness, it can be very
1174         * unpredictable in how it handles saturation. Most colors between 0.5 and 0.75 hue that also have less than 0.5
1175         * lightness are extremely desaturated and close to gray, regardless of what you give for saturation, and these
1176         * colors suddenly jump to very saturated around 0.75 hue and higher. To avoid this issue, you may prefer using
1177         * {@link #oklabByHCL(float, float, float, float)}, which takes an absolute chroma as opposed to the saturation here
1178         * (which is a fraction of the maximum chroma).
1179         * <br>
1180         * Note that this takes a different value for its {@code hue} that the method {@link #hue(float)} produces, just
1181         * like its {@code saturation} and the method {@link #saturation(float)}, and {@code lightness} and the method
1182         * {@link #lightness(float)}. The hue is just distributed differently, and the lightness should be equivalent to
1183         * {@link #channelL(float)}, but the saturation here refers to what fraction the chroma should be of the maximum
1184         * chroma for the given hue and lightness. You can use {@link #oklabHue(float)}, {@link #oklabSaturation(float)},
1185         * and {@link #oklabLightness(float)} to get the hue, saturation, and lightness values from an existing color that
1186         * this will understand ({@link #alpha(float)} too).
1187         * @param hue between 0 and 1, usually, but this will automatically wrap if too high or too low
1188         * @param saturation will be clamped between 0 and 1
1189         * @param lightness will be clamped between 0 and 1
1190         * @param alpha will be clamped between 0 and 1
1191         * @return a packed Oklab float color that tries to match the requested hue, saturation, and lightness
1192         */
1193        public static float oklabByHSL(float hue, float saturation, float lightness, float alpha) {
1194                lightness = Math.min(Math.max(lightness, 0f), 1f);
1195                saturation = Math.min(Math.max(saturation, 0f), 1f);
1196                hue -= MathUtils.floor(hue);
1197                alpha = Math.min(Math.max(alpha, 0f), 1f);
1198                final int idx = (int) (lightness * 255.999f) << 8 | (int) (256f * hue);
1199                final float dist = GAMUT_DATA[idx] * saturation;
1200                return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(
1201                                (int) (alpha * 127.999f) << 25 |
1202                                                (int) (TrigTools.sin_(hue) * dist + 128f) << 16 |
1203                                                (int) (TrigTools.cos_(hue) * dist + 128f) << 8 |
1204                                                (int) (lightness * 255.999f));
1205        }

1208         * A different way to specify an Oklab color, using hue, chroma, lightness, and alpha something like a normal HSL(A)
1209         * color but calculating them directly in the Oklab color space. This has you specify the desired chroma directly,
1210         * as obtainable with {@link #chroma(float)}, rather than the saturation, which is a fraction of the maximum chroma
1211         * (saturation is what {@link #oklabByHSL(float, float, float, float)} uses). Note that this takes a different value
1212         * for its {@code hue} that the method {@link #hue(float)} produces, just like {@code lightness} and the method
1213         * {@link #lightness(float)}. The hue is just distributed differently, and the lightness should be equivalent to
1214         * {@link #channelL(float)}. If you use this to get two colors with the same chroma and lightness, but different
1215         * hue, then the resulting colors should have similar colorfulness unless one or both chroma values exceeded the
1216         * gamut limit (you can get this limit with {@link #chromaLimit(float, float)}). If a chroma value given is greater
1217         * than the chroma limit, this clamps chroma to that limit. You can use {@link #oklabHue(float)},
1218         * {@link #chroma(float)}, and {@link #oklabLightness(float)} to get the hue, chroma, and lightness values from an
1219         * existing color that this will understand ({@link #alpha(float)} too).
1220         * @param hue between 0 and 1, usually, but this will automatically wrap if too high or too low
1221         * @param chroma will be clamped between 0 and the maximum chroma possible for the given hue and lightness
1222         * @param lightness will be clamped between 0 and 1
1223         * @param alpha will be clamped between 0 and 1
1224         * @return a packed Oklab float color that tries to match the requested hue, chroma, and lightness
1225         */
1226        public static float oklabByHCL(float hue, float chroma, float lightness, float alpha) {
1227                lightness = Math.min(Math.max(lightness, 0f), 1f);
1228                chroma = Math.max(chroma, 0f);
1229                hue -= MathUtils.floor(hue);
1230                alpha = Math.min(Math.max(alpha, 0f), 1f);
1231                final int idx = (int) (lightness * 255.999f) << 8 | (int) (256f * hue);
1232                final float dist = Math.min(chroma * 127.5f, GAMUT_DATA[idx]);
1233                return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(
1234                                (int) (alpha * 127.999f) << 25 |
1235                                                (int) (TrigTools.sin_(hue) * dist + 127.5f) << 16 |
1236                                                (int) (TrigTools.cos_(hue) * dist + 127.5f) << 8 |
1237                                                (int) (lightness * 255.999f));
1238        }

1240        /**
1241         * Checks whether the given Oklab color is in-gamut; if it isn't in-gamut, brings the color just inside
1242         * the gamut at the same lightness, or if it is already in-gamut, returns the color as-is.
1243         * @param packed a packed float color in Oklab format; often this color is not in-gamut
1244         * @return the first color this finds that is in-gamut, as if it was moving toward a grayscale color with the same L
1245         * @see #inGamut(float) You can use inGamut() if you just want to check whether a color is in-gamut.
1246         */
1247        public static float limitToGamut(final float packed) {
1248                final int decoded = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(packed);
1249                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f);
1250                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f);
1251                final float hue = TrigTools.atan2_(B, A);
1252                final int idx = (decoded & 0xff) << 8 | (int) (256f * hue);
1253                final float dist = GAMUT_DATA[idx];
1254                if (dist * dist * 0.25f >= (A * A + B * B))
1255                        return packed;
1256                return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(
1257                                (decoded & 0xFE0000FF) |
1258                                                (int) (TrigTools.cos_(hue) * dist + 128f) << 8 |
1259                                                (int) (TrigTools.sin_(hue) * dist + 128f) << 16);
1260        }

1262        /**
1263         * Checks whether the given Oklab color is in-gamut; if it isn't in-gamut, brings the color just inside
1264         * the gamut at the same lightness, or if it is already in-gamut, returns the color as-is. This always produces
1265         * an opaque color.
1266         * @param L lightness component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1267         * @param A green-to-red chromatic component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1268         * @param B blue-to-yellow chromatic component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1269         * @return the first color this finds that is in-gamut, as if it was moving toward a grayscale color with the same L
1270         * @see #inGamut(float, float, float)  You can use inGamut() if you just want to check whether a color is in-gamut.
1271         */
1272        public static float limitToGamut(float L, float A, float B) {
1273                return limitToGamut(L, A, B, 1f);
1274        }
1275        /**
1276         * Checks whether the given Oklab color is in-gamut; if it isn't in-gamut, brings the color just inside
1277         * the gamut at the same lightness, or if it is already in-gamut, returns the color as-is.
1278         * @param L lightness component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1279         * @param A green-to-red chromatic component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1280         * @param B blue-to-yellow chromatic component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1281         * @param alpha alpha component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1282         * @return the first color this finds that is in-gamut, as if it was moving toward a grayscale color with the same L
1283         * @see #inGamut(float, float, float)  You can use inGamut() if you just want to check whether a color is in-gamut.
1284         */
1285        public static float limitToGamut(float L, float A, float B, float alpha) {
1286                L = Math.min(Math.max(L, 0f), 1f);
1287                A = Math.min(Math.max(A, 0f), 1f);
1288                B = Math.min(Math.max(B, 0f), 1f);
1289                alpha = Math.min(Math.max(alpha, 0f), 1f);
1290                final float A2 = (A - 0.5f);
1291                final float B2 = (B - 0.5f);
1292                final float hue = TrigTools.atan2_(B2, A2);
1293                final int idx = (int) (L * 255.999f) << 8 | (int)(256f * hue);
1294                final float dist = GAMUT_DATA[idx];
1295                if(dist * dist * 0x1p-18f >= (A2 * A2 + B2 * B2))
1296                        return oklab(L, A, B, alpha);
1297                return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(
1298                                (int) (alpha * 127.999f) << 25 |
1299                                                (int) (TrigTools.sin_(hue) * dist + 128f) << 16 |
1300                                                (int) (TrigTools.cos_(hue) * dist + 128f) << 8 |
1301                                                (int) (L * 255.999f));
1302        }

1304        /**
1305         * Given a packed float Oklab color, this edits its L, A, B, and alpha channels by adding the corresponding "add"
1306         * parameter and then clamping. This returns a different float value (of course, the given float can't be edited
1307         * in-place). You can give a value of 0 for any "add" parameter you want to stay unchanged. This clamps the
1308         * resulting color to remain in-gamut, so it should be safe to convert it back to RGBA.
1309         * @param encoded a packed float Oklab color
1310         * @param addL how much to add to the L channel; typically in the -1 to 1 range
1311         * @param addA how much to add to the A channel; typically in the -1 to 1 range
1312         * @param addB how much to add to the B channel; typically in the -1 to 1 range
1313         * @param addAlpha how much to add to the alpha channel; typically in the -1 to 1 range
1314         * @return a packed float Oklab color with the requested edits applied to {@code encoded}
1315         */
1316        public static float editOklab(float encoded, float addL, float addA, float addB, float addAlpha) {
1317                return editOklab(encoded, addL, addA, addB, addAlpha, 1f, 1f, 1f, 1f);
1318        }
1319        /**
1320         * Given a packed float Oklab color, this edits its L, A, B, and alpha channels by first multiplying each channel by
1321         * the corresponding "mul" parameter and then adding the corresponding "add" parameter, before clamping. This means
1322         * the lightness value {@code L} is multiplied by {@code mulL}, then has {@code addL} added, and then is clamped to
1323         * the normal range for L (0 to 1). This returns a different float value (of course, the given float can't be edited
1324         * in-place). You can give a value of 0 for any "add" parameter you want to stay unchanged, or a value of 1 for any
1325         * "mul" parameter that shouldn't change. Note that this manipulates A and B in the -0.5 to 0.5 range, so if you
1326         * multiply by a small number like {@code 0.25f}, then this will produce a less-saturated color, and if you multiply
1327         * by a larger number like {@code 4f}, then you will get a much more-saturated color. This clamps the resulting
1328         * color to remain in-gamut, so it should be safe to convert it back to RGBA.
1329         * @param encoded a packed float Oklab color
1330         * @param addL how much to add to the L channel; typically in the -1 to 1 range
1331         * @param addA how much to add to the A channel; typically in the -1 to 1 range
1332         * @param addB how much to add to the B channel; typically in the -1 to 1 range
1333         * @param addAlpha how much to add to the alpha channel; typically in the -1 to 1 range
1334         * @param mulL how much to multiply the L channel by; should be non-negative
1335         * @param mulA how much to multiply the A channel by; usually non-negative (not always)
1336         * @param mulB how much to multiply the B channel by; usually non-negative (not always)
1337         * @param mulAlpha how much to multiply the alpha channel by; should be non-negative
1338         * @return a packed float Oklab color with the requested edits applied to {@code encoded}
1339         */
1340        public static float editOklab(float encoded, float addL, float addA, float addB, float addAlpha,
1341                                                                  float mulL, float mulA, float mulB, float mulAlpha) {
1342                final int decoded = NumberUtils.floatToRawIntBits(encoded);
1343                float L = (decoded & 0xff) / 255f;
1344                float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
1345                float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
1346                float alpha = (decoded >>> 25) / 127f;
1347
1348                L = Math.min(Math.max(L * mulL + addL, 0f), 1f);
1349                A = Math.min(Math.max(A * mulA + addA * 2f, -1f), 1f) * 0.5f;
1350                B = Math.min(Math.max(B * mulB + addB * 2f, -1f), 1f) * 0.5f;
1351                alpha = Math.min(Math.max(alpha * mulAlpha + addAlpha, 0f), 1f);
1352                final float hue = TrigTools.atan2_(B, A);
1353                final int idx = (int) (L * 255.999f) << 8 | (int)(256f * hue);
1354                final float dist = GAMUT_DATA[idx] ;
1355                if(dist * dist * 0x1p-18f >= (A * A + B * B))
1356                        return oklab(L, A + 0.5f, B + 0.5f, alpha);
1357                return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(
1358                                (int) (alpha * 127.999f) << 25 |
1359                                                (int) (TrigTools.sin_(hue) * dist + 128f) << 16 |
1360                                                (int) (TrigTools.cos_(hue) * dist + 128f) << 8 |
1361                                                (int) (L * 255.999f));
1362        }

1364        /**
1365         * Produces a random packed float color that is always in-gamut (and opaque) and should be uniformly distributed.
1366         * @param random a Random object (preferably a subclass of Random, like {@link com.badlogic.gdx.math.RandomXS128})
1367         * @return a packed float color that is always in-gamut
1368         */
1369        public static float randomColor(Random random) {
1370                float L = random.nextFloat();
1371                float A = random.nextFloat();
1372                float B = random.nextFloat();
1373                while (!inGamut(L, A, B)) {
1374                        L = random.nextFloat();
1375                        A = random.nextFloat();
1376                        B = random.nextFloat();
1377                }
1378                return oklab(L, A, B, 1f);
1379        }
